@section Simulation


As explained in @ref{d,,What is GHDL?}, @cite{GHDL} is a compiler which translates @cite{VHDL} files to machine code.
Hence, the regular workflow is composed of three steps:


@itemize *

@item 
@ref{4a,,Analysis [-a]}: convert design units (@cite{VHDL} sources) to an internal representation.

@item 
@ref{4b,,Elaboration [-e]}: generate executable machine code for a target module (top-level entity).

@item 
@ref{4c,,Run [-r]}: execute the design to test the behaviour, generate output/waveforms, etc.
@end itemize

The following tips might be useful:


@itemize *

@item 
Don’t forget to select the version of the VHDL standard you want to use (see @ref{4d,,VHDL standards}).
The default is @ref{4e,,--std=93c}.
Use @ref{4e,,--std=08} for VHDL-2008 (albeit not fully implemented).


@itemize *

@item 
Use @ref{4f,,--ieee=synopsys} if your design depends on a non-standard implementation of the IEEE library.

@item 
Use @ref{50,,-fexplicit} and @ref{51,,-frelaxed-rules} if needed.
For instance, if you would like to use VHDL 2008 and also use shared variables with an ordinary type (deprecated in
VHDL 2000), you can use @code{--std=08 -frelaxed-rules}.
@end itemize

@item 
Use @ref{52,,--work=LIB_NAME} to analyze files into the @code{LIB_NAME} library.
To use files analyzed to a different directory, give the path to the @code{LIB_NAME} library using
-P/path/to/name/directory/@footnote{https://docs.python.org/3/using/cmdline.html#cmdoption-P}.

@item 
Use the same options for analysis and elaboration.
E.g., first analyse with @code{ghdl -a --std=08 --work=mylib myfile.vhdl}; and then elaborate and run with
@code{ghdl --elab-run --std=08 top}.
@end itemize

Due to the fact that @cite{VHDL} is processed as a general purpose language (instead of an @cite{HDL}), all the language features
are to be supported.
I.e., @cite{VHDL} sources do not need to be limited to the synthesisable subset.
However, distinction between synthesisable and non-synthesisable (simulation-only) subsets is often misleading for users
who are new to the language.
Different examples are provided, in the hope of helping understand the different use cases:

